{"title_page": "Quiz (play)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox play\n| name       =Quiz\n| image      =Quiz (play).jpg\n| image_size =350px \n| caption    =Official poster of the 2018 West End production\n| writer     =[[James Graham (playwright)|James Graham]]\n| chorus     = \n| characters =\n| mute       = \n| setting    =2001, ''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? (UK game show)|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]]''\n| premiere   = {{Start date|df=yes|2017|11|10}}\n| place      =[[Minerva Theatre, Chichester]]\n| orig_lang  =English\n| series     = \n| subject    = \n| genre      =\n}}\n'''''Quiz''''' is a [[Play (theatre)|play]] written by [[James Graham (playwright)|James Graham]]. Originally commissioned by theatre producer, William Village,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.williamvillage.com/|title=William Village {{!}} Independent theatre producer and general manager|last=Village|first=William|website=William Village|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-02}}</ref> it made its world premiere at the [[Minerva Theatre, Chichester]], in November 2017, before transferring to the [[Noel Coward Theatre]] in London's [[West End theatre|West End]] in March 2018. The play centres on the true story of [[Charles Ingram]] and [[R v Ingram, C., Ingram, D. and Whittock, T.|the coughing scandal]] that surrounded his 2001 win of \u00a31,000,000 on ''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? (UK game show)|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]]''.<ref name = \"Cough\"/> In 2020, the stage play was adapted for a TV series.\n\n==Background==\n''Quiz'' is written by British playwright [[James Graham (playwright)|James Graham]].<ref name=\"Cough\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-43700097| title=Millionaire cough scandal: 'The most British crime of all time' | publisher=[[BBC News]] | date=12 April 2018 | accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref> The play centres around the true story of [[Charles Ingram]] (who later came to be known as \"the Coughing Major\")<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/vdqdw9/15-years-of-the-coughing-major-who-wants-to-be-a-millionare |title=15 years since \"the Coughing Major\" |work=Vice |accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> and the coughing scandal that surrounded his 2001 win of \u00a31,000,000 on ''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? (UK game show)|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]]'' and the subsequent court trial.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/theatre/what-to-see/wants-millionaire-scandal-inspires-new-play-happened-next-coughing/| title=Who Wants to be Millionaire scandal inspires new play: what happened next to the coughing Major? | work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] | date=16 February 2017 | accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref> \n\nCharles Ingram, a major in the [[British Army]] entered British quiz show ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'' in September 2001. Suspicions arose during filming after coughing was heard loudly adjacent to the correct answers. A sound technician informed [[Celador]] CEO Paul Smith of their suspicions, with filming allowed to continue and the tapes reviewed after filming had completed.<ref name=mf /> Ingram eventually won the million pounds,<ref name=mf /> however upon reviewing the tapes and each cough heard, Ingram was accused of cheating by having his wife, Diana, and an accomplice, Tecwen Whittock, cough as Ingram announced the correct answer from the available choices.<ref name=mf /><ref>{{cite web|author=Jonathan Evans |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/coughing-major-welsh-accomplice-who-8467202 |title=\"Coughing Major\" and his Welsh accomplice, who cheated their way to Who Wants To Be A Millionaire? jackpot, release new book claiming innocence |work=Wales Online |date=17 January 2015 |accessdate=4 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=bt>{{cite web |url=http://home.bt.com/news/on-this-day/september-10-2001-we-dont-want-to-give-you-that-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-bosses-tell-cheating-major-charles-ingram-11364002461687 |title=We don't want to give you that, Who Wants to be a Millionaire bosses tell 'cheating major' Charles Ingram |publisher=BT |date=10 September 2016 |accessdate=4 January 2018}}</ref> Ingram \"refuted\" the claims.<ref name=mf>{{cite episode\n| title = Who Wants To Be A Millionaire?: Major Fraud\n| episodelink = \n| series = Who Wants To Be A Millionaire?\n| serieslink =Who Wants To Be A Millionaire?\n| credits =\n| network =[[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n| station = [[ITV1]]\n| location = \n| airdate = 8 May 2003\n| began =\n| ended =\n| season =\n| seriesno =\n| number = 1\n| minutes = \n| transcript =\n| transcripturl= }}\n</ref>\n\nFollowing [[R v Ingram, C., Ingram, D. and Whittock, T.|trial]] on 7 April 2003, a jury declared the Ingrams and Whittock guilty of [[procuring the execution of a valuable security by deception]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.insidetime.org/%EF%BF%BCbad-show-quiz-cough-millionaire-major/ |title=Bad show: The Quiz, The Cough and the Millionaire Major |work=Inside Time |accessdate=4 January 2018}}</ref> The Ingrams were sentenced to an 18-month [[suspended sentence]] and a fine of \u00a315,000 plus \u00a310,000 for costs each. Whittock received a 12-month suspended sentence with a \u00a310,000 fine plus a \u00a37,500 costs order.<ref name=jail>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/2910119.stm |title=Millionaire trio escape jail |publisher=BBC News |date=8 April 2003 |accessdate=4 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nGraham was a teenager when ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'' first appeared on British television in 1998<ref name = \"teen\"/> and became \"fixated\" by the subsequent trial and what he describes as the most \"British crime in the history of the world.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/theatre/james-graham-on-why-the-quiz-scandal-is-the-most-british-crime-in-history-a3811246.html| title=James Graham on why the Quiz scandal is 'the most British crime in history'| work=[[Evening Standard]] | date=11 April 2018 | accessdate=3 May 2018}}</ref> He later received a copy of the 2015 book ''Bad Show: The Quiz, the Cough, the Millionaire Major''.<ref name=\"teen\">{{cite web | url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/james-graham-interview-the-playwright-on-quiz-his-take-on-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-gt9rr9233?_ga=2.81293847.1891980050.1525204950-537077985.1525204950| title=James Graham interview: the playwright on Quiz, his take on Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?| work=[[The Times]]  | date=1 April 2018 | accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref> It raised questions about the case and raised the possibility that Ingram was innocent of all charges<ref name=\"innocent\">{{cite web | url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2015/02/from-umbrella-man-to-the-coughing-major-the-truth-is-often-very-strange/| title=From Umbrella Man to the Coughing Major, the truth is often very strange| work=[[The Spectator]] | date=11 April 2018 | accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref> and forms the basis of which ''Quiz'' was adapted.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.chichester.co.uk/whats-on/theatre-and-comedy/the-coughing-major-comes-to-the-stage-1-8230899 | title=The \"coughing major\" comes to the stage...| work=Chichester Observer| date=6 November 2017| accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref> In February 2017,<ref name=\"season\">{{cite web | url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/theatre/chichester-festival-theatre-2017-season-will-feature-ian-mckellen-as-king-lear-and-a-new-play-from-a3468131.html | title=Chichester Festival Theatre 2017 season will feature Ian McKellen as King Lear and a new play from Edna O'Brien| work=[[Evening Standard]]  | date=16 February 2017 | accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref> it was announced the play would premiere at the [[Minerva Theatre, Chichester|Minerva Theatre]], part of the [[Chichester Festival Theatre]].<ref name = \"What\"/> The play is directed by [[Daniel Evans (actor)|Daniel Evans]],<ref name=\"direction\">{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/mar/18/daniel-evans-interview-chichester-festival-theatre-quiz| title=Daniel Evans: 'I am quite unashamedly a populist. I like making big shows in big spaces'| work=[[The Guardian]]  | date=18 March 2018 | accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref> with movement direction by Naomi Said,<ref>{{cite book |last=Graham |first=James |date=2 April 2018 |title=Quiz |url= |location= |publisher=[[Methuen Drama]] |page=6 |isbn=978-1-3500-6929-9 |author-link= }}</ref>  design by Robert Jones,<ref name=\"design\">{{cite web | url=http://www.playbill.com/article/james-grahams-quiz-based-on-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-scandal-will-transfer-to-west-end| title=James Graham's Quiz, Based on Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? Scandal, Will Transfer to West End| work=[[Playbill]] | date=1 December 2017 | accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref> lighting design by Tim Lutkin,<ref name = \"design\"/> video design by [[Tim Reid]]<ref name=\"video\">{{cite web | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/quiz-theater-1101874| title='Quiz': Theater Review| work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=11 April 2018 | accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref> and music and sound design by Ben and Max Ringham.<ref name = \"design\"/>\n\n==Productions ==\n=== Chichester ===\n\n''Quiz'' began previews at the [[Minerva Theatre, Chichester|Minerva Theatre]], on 3 November 2017, with an official opening night on 10 November,<ref name=\"What\">{{cite web | url=https://www.whatsonstage.com/chichester-theatre/news/casting-james-graham-quiz-gavin-spokes_44687.html| title=Casting announced for new James Graham play Quiz | work=Whats On Stage | date=21 September 2017 | accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref> running until 2 December.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/news/2017/daniel-evans-unveils-inaugural-chichester-festival-theatre-season/| title=Djalili and McKellen to star in Daniel Evans' first Chichester Festival Theatre season| work=[[The Stage]]  | date=16 February 2017 | accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref> Due to demand the run was extended to 9 December 2017.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cft.org.uk/news/quiz-extends-to-9-december| title=Quiz Extends To 9 December| publisher=[[Chichester Festival Theatre]] | date=31 March 2017 | accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref> Notable casting included Gavin Spokes and Stephanie Street as [[Charles Ingram|Charles]] and Diana Ingram, with Keir Charles playing [[Chris Tarrant]].<ref name=\"charachters\">{{cite book |last=Graham |first=James |date=2 April 2018 |title=Quiz |url= |location= |publisher=[[Methuen Drama]] |page=5 |isbn=978-1-3500-6929-9 |author-link= }}</ref><ref name = \"Chichester\"/> \n\n=== West End ===\n\nFollowing its premiere production the play transferred to the [[West End theatre|West End]]'s [[No\u00ebl Coward Theatre]] where it began previews on 31 March 2018, with an official opening night on 10 April, booking for a limited period until 16 June.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/news/2017/james-grahams-quiz-announces-west-end-transfer/| title=James Graham's Quiz announces West End transfer| work=[[The Stage]] | date=1 December 2017 | accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.whatsonstage.com/west-end-theatre/news/james-graham-quiz-west-end-transfer-who-wants-millionaire_45259.html| title=James Graham's Quiz to transfer to the West End | work=Whats On Stage | date=1 December 2017 | accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref> It was produced by William Village, Playful Productions and Chichester Festival Theatre<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/news/2017/james-grahams-quiz-announces-west-end-transfer/|title=James Graham\u2019s Quiz announces West End transfer|date=2017-12-01|work=The Stage|access-date=2018-06-20|language=en-US}}</ref>. Sharon Ballard joined the original cast for the London run.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://officiallondontheatre.com/news/quiz-announces-west-end-transfer-casting-111407555/| title=Quiz announced West End On Stage Seating And Casting| work=Official London Theatre  | date=25 January 2018 | accessdate=4 May 2018}}</ref> Prior to the production transferring around 40% of the play was rewritten by Graham<ref name = \"Cough\"/>  and on stage seating added to provide a more studio like environment for audiences.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/james-graham-quiz-west-end-millionaire-seating_45619.html| title=James Graham's Quiz West End transfer to have onstage seating| work=Whats On Stage | date=25 January 2018 | accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref> Explaining the extensive rewrite Graham explained that the changes were:<blockquote>not because we weren't happy with what happened in Chichester, but you learn so much when you do a tryout for a show, so we streamlined the narrative, I reordered some of the structure, we had to think about a West End proscenium Victorian theatre, which is very different to a studio theatre in Chichester.<ref name = \"Cough\"/></blockquote> In addition, people that were involved in the production of ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'' had seen the show in Chichester and had provided additional information, which in turn had allowed Graham to enhance the play. One who attended, but in disguise, was the erstwhile host of the show, Chris Tarrant. He would later write a piece for the ''Daily Mail'' saying the show was entertaining but Ingram was guilty. <ref name = \"Cough\"/>\n\nThe audience are given the opportunity to act as the jury via electronic voting<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2017/nov/19/quiz-minerva-chichester-review-james-graham-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire | title=James Graham has all the right answers| work=[[The Guardian]]| date=19 November 2017 | accessdate=28 April 2018}}</ref> after each act, where they will have witnessed the arguments for the prosecution and the defence to decide whether Ingram was guilty.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/reviews/quiz-review-noel-coward-theatre-who-wants-millionaire-cast-tickets-james-graham-a8299351.html | title=In James Graham's Who Wants to Be a Millionaire play, the audience is the jury of the 'coughing major'| work=[[The Independent]]  | date=11 April 2018 | accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://inews.co.uk/news/writer-rejects-chris-tarrant-criticism-of-coughing-major-millionaire-play-quiz/ | title=Did the 'Coughing Major' cheat on Who Wants To Be A Millionaire? At new West End play Quiz you get to decide| work=[[i (newspaper)|I]]  | date=11 April 2018 | accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe West End production was nominated for two Olivier Awards in 2019: Best New Comedy and Best Actor in a Supporting Role (Keir Charles).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://officiallondontheatre.com/olivier-awards/year/2019/|title=Winners list for the Olivier Awards 2019 with Mastercard {{!}} Official Website|website=Olivier Awards|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref>\n\n=== UK & Ireland Tour ===\n\nQuiz will tour the UK and Ireland between August - November 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://quiztheplay.co.uk/|title=Quiz the Play|website=Quiz the Play Official Website|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n\n==TV adaptation==\n\nIn 2019, filming began on a three-part TV series for ITV adapted from the play (written by and executive produced by Graham) to air on 13-15 April 2020, directed by [[Stephen Frears]] and starring [[Michael Sheen]] as Chris Tarrant, [[Matthew Macfadyen]] as Charles Ingram, [[Sian Clifford]] as Diana Ingram and [[Michael Jibson]] as Tecwen Whittock.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/quiz-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-stephen-frears-michael-sheen-1203304574/|title=ITV and AMC Order \u2018Who Wants to Be a Millionaire\u2019 Cheating Drama \u2018Quiz\u2019|last=Littleton|first=Cynthia|date=16 August 2019|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=16 August 2019}}</ref> The series is produced by Alice Pearse, and executive produced by Dan Winch, William Village, James Graham, Stephen Frears and Andy Harries. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/press-releases/itv-commissions-three-part-drama-quiz-directed-stephen-frears-and-produced-left-bank|title=ITV commissions three-part drama, Quiz, directed by Stephen Frears and produced by Left Bank Pictures|website=Press Centre|language=en|access-date=2019-08-19}}</ref>\n\n==Principal roles and original cast == \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Character\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Stage play<ref name=\"Chichester\">{{cite web | url=https://www.cft.org.uk/archive/quiz#cast-and-creatives| title=QUIZ Cast and Creatives | publisher=Chichester Festival Theatre | work=cft.org.uk | accessdate=28 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"characters\">{{cite book |last=Graham |first=James |date=2 April 2018 |title=Quiz |url= |location= |publisher=[[Methuen Drama]] |page=5 |isbn=978-1-3500-6929-9 |author-link= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.playbill.com/article/west-end-transfer-of-quiz-finds-its-cast | title=West End Transfer of Quiz Finds Its Cast | work=[[Playbill]]  | date=25 January 2018 | accessdate=28 April 2018}}</ref>\n!ITV Drama\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Charles Ingram]]\n| align=\"center\"|Gavin Spokes\n|align=\"center\"|[[Matthew Macfadyen]]\n|- \n! scope=\"row\" |[[Diana Ingram]]\n| align=\"center\"|Stephanie Street\n|align=\"center\" |Sian Clifford\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Rachel da Costa\n| align=\"center\"|Sharon Ballard\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Nicholas Hilliard (judge)|Nicholas Hilliard QC]] / Quizmaster / [[John de Mol Jr.|John de Mol]]\n| align=\"center\"|[[Paul Bazely]]\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Warm Up / [[Chris Tarrant]] / [[Jim Bowen]] / [[Des O'Connor]] / [[Leslie Crowther]]\n| align=\"center\"|Keir Charles\n| align=\"center\" | [[Michael Sheen]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Paul Smith / Paddy Spooner / Adrian Woolfe\n| align=\"center\"|Greg Haiste\n| align=\"center\" | [[Mark Bonnar]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Tecwen Whittock]] / [[